Fascinated with portraiture, female representation and photographic history, Chloe Parker's 'CODENAME EWOL'
(re-)presents vintage objects in the present day. In 2016 she had unexpectedly purchased the suitcase of Ms. Frances Florence Lowe at a local auction. The contents revealed the life of a mysterious woman. Through her rigorous research to learn more about Ms. Lowe, the investigatory series exposes the working and living conditions of women who were resistance members, code breakers and spies during WW2. The work details a range of ephemera found in the suitcase including photographs, letters and documents. EMBRACE "It's the #film the #Aussie censors didn't want you to see with your teens and tweens.." @nzstuff
Released in #Australia in August 2016 as 15+, now on #Netflix! #watchnow
The heart of it is Taryn’s story... Had a baby, went into a #bodybuilding regime to stand on stage in a #bikini. Only to realize job not done. The story of how she went from being a body hater to a body lover. Her unconventional before - after picture went viral... seen by 100 million people #worldwide.
"As a piece of storytelling, #Embrace is similarly intimate and idiosyncratic. And that's what makes it so accessible." @newscomauhq
A @sydfilmfest premiere, it was the photo that sparked the #australian #documentary's Kickstarter campaign, with over 9000 contributors... with the fundraising trailer having more than 25 million views online! "Embrace, cleverly, identifies #bodyimage as a hugely #feminist issue not just from the perspective of weight, but disability, gender #identity, ethnicity, and age." @filmink
#TarynBrumfitt traveled #aroundtheworld meeting women with their own body image stories to tell.
"Our body is not an ornament but a vehicle", says Taryn Bruffit. #selflove
P.S. The #Adelaide based mother-of-three now runs a Body Image movement.
